SPARC Europe Announces Award for Outstanding=20
Achievements in Scholarly Communications


Oxford, UK =AD SPARC Europe (Scholarly Publishing=20
and Academic Resources Coalition), a leading=20
organization of European research libraries,=20
today announced the inauguration of the SPARC=20
Europe Award for Outstanding Achievements in=20
Scholarly Communications.  The new annual Award=20
will be presented to an individual or group=20
within Europe that has made significant advances=20
in our understanding of the issues surrounding=20
scholarly communications and/or in developing=20
practical means to address the problems with the current systems.
The judging panel, formed from members of the=20
SPARC Europe Board of Directors, has issued a=20
call for nominations for the Award.  Nominations=20
are open to all who have made major contributions=20
in the field of scholarly communications, and the=20
judging panel particularly wishes to receive=20
nominations of individuals of groups working in any of the following areas:


Research that helps illuminate the scholarly communications landscape
Advocacy for new models of scholarly communications
Development of new tools to aid scholarly=20
communication (e.g. repository software)
Interesting new projects or products
Implementation of policies that promote new scholarly communication models.


Nominations (together with a short outline of the=20
nominee=92s work) should be sent to David Prosser,=20
Director of SPARC Europe no later than 10th=20
February 2006. The Award will be present at the=20
Third Nordic Conference on Scholarly=20
Communication, to be held at Lund, Sweden 24 - 25 April 2006.

<http://www.sparceurope.org/>SPARC Europe is an=20
alliance of 110 research-led university libraries=20
from 14 European countries. It is affiliated with=20
<http://www.arl.org/sparc/>SPARC based in=20
Washington, D.C., which represents over 200=20
institutions, mainly in North America. SPARC=20
Europe and SPARC work to develop and promote new=20
models of scholarly communication that increase=20
the access to and utility of the research literature.

David C Prosser PhD
Director
SPARC Europe

